<DOCNO> AP900819-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
us warships fired the first shots by american forces in the 
persian gulf crisis in an unsuccessful effort to halt two iraqi 
tankers and iraq said thousands of foreign captives will suffer 
first if a us blockade curtails food 
iraqs threat which singled out foreign babies and elderly 
people was immediately denounced by the white house as an illegal 
use of innocent civilians as pawns in the middle east standoff 
the un security council late saturday unanimously demanded 
that iraq let all foreigners leave and that baghdad take no 
action to jeopardize the safety security or health of such 
nationals 
 
iraqs statement coupled with an earlier threat to use 
americans and other foreigners as a defensive shield for iraqi 
military installations made it clear the foreigners have become a 
central part of iraqs antius strategy 
iraq said saturday it had begun moving some of the foreigners to 
strategic locations around the country 
in washington the pentagon said the uss reid fired six warning 
shots across the bow of the iraqi ship khanaqin in the gulf of oman 
after it refused repeated requests to halt 
the shots were the first fired in the 2dayold interdiction 
effort ordered by president bush to halt goods leaving and entering 
iraq 
also the uss bradley fired three warning shots across the bow 
of another iraqi tanker to the north in the persian gulf and headed 
toward the gulf of oman the pentagon said 
the persian gulf which connects with the gulf of oman is 
iraqs outlet to the sea 
both tankers are currently under way but are under close us 
navy surveillance the pentagon said a pentagon source who spoke 
on condition of anonymity said navy ships were unlikely to take 
further action against the ships during nighttime hours 
the pentagon said the iraqi vessels which were heading out of 
the persian gulf area were believed carrying iraqi oil 
baghdad said the tankers were not hit and continued on their 
way but that a similar act in the future will have grave 
consequences 
iraqs foreign minister tariq aziz said he did not consider 
the iraqi treatment of foreigners an act of war merely an attempt 
to prevent us forces massing in saudi arabia from attacking iraq 
or kuwait 
foreigners would live with the iraqis in some places that are 
the target of probable american aggression aziz told cbs news 
that might deter the american government from committing the 
crime that the iraqi people would like to avoid 
in an interview saturday with britains independent television 
news iraqi ambassador to france abdul razzak alhachimi said in 
paris some of them the foreigners have been distributed in 
strategic installations in iraq starting all the way from north of 
iraq to the south 
thomas r pickering the us ambassador to the united nations 
said later saturday that iraqs actions over the past 24 hours make 
it clear that iraqi president saddam hussein is going to hold 
hostage all foreigners 
us officials had previously avoided using the word hostage 
to refer to the americans and other foreigners trapped in iraq and 
kuwait 
the british foreign office said 40 britons five americans four 
germans and one french citizen were moved from kuwaiti hotels to 
undisclosed locations aziz told cbs that iraq will not use 
chemicals weapons unless the united states uses nuclear weapons in 
the conflict 
however iraqs army newspaper on saturday reiterated a threat 
to use weapons of mass destruction against any attacker an 
apparent reference to iraqs arsenal of longrange missiles nerve 
gas and mustard gas 
the united states meanwhile continued to pour thousands of 
troops into saudi arabia in an effort to build up a force that 
could withstand an invasion by tens of thousands of iraqi soldiers 
massed on the saudikuwait border 
for the first time since iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 and later 
annexed the emirate us troops stationed in the saudi desert 
conducted maneuvers at night in temperatures that still hovered 
around 95 degrees 
were here sweating because our lives may depend on it said 
one private who carried a 50pound pack friday night but its 
really not up to us our lives are in the politicians hands 
finding the courage is tough said a medic traveling with 
the soldiers its scary out here but youve got to swallow that 
and go out and do it 
in other developments 
president bush prepared to call up military reserves to fill in 
the ranks of military doctors cargo handlers and other 
specialists an army source said as many as 80000 reservists and 
national guardsmen could be activated 
the pentagon launched an unprecedented diversion of civilian 
aircraft to bolster the us military presence in the middle east 
defense secretary dick cheney said the us military commitment 
to saudi arabias defense is longterm where well be a year 
or two from now i wouldnt want to speculate he said while en 
route to saudi arabia 
iraq which made peace overtures to iran in order to devote its 
full attention to the standoff with the united states withdrew 
thousands of troops from its iranian border and said they would be 
deployed near saudi arabia 
saudi arabia said it is ready to increase its oil output by up 
to 2 million barrels a day to help offset the shortfall caused by 
the iraqi invasion but a saudi minister said that would leave 
world markets 2 million barrels short of preinvasion levels and 
it may not halt soaring gas and oil prices 
thousands of arabs continued to reach jordan after fleeing from 
iraq and iraqoccupied kuwait the only westerners to get out were 
the few brave enough to dash for the border in private cars 
the baghdad government holds 3000 americans 4000 britons and 
about 14000 other westerners among the more than 2 million 
foreigners caught in iraq and kuwait when iraqi troops invaded 
kuwait on aug 2 
</TEXT>
