<DOCNO> AP900819-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
three teenagers were convicted saturday of 
raping and assaulting a woman jogger who was brutalized and left 
for dead in central park by a marauding gang of youths 
the defendants antron mccray 16 yusef salaam 16 and raymond 
santana 15 were found innocent of sodomy and of attempted 
murder the most serious charge in the muchpublicized case they 
also were convicted of riot 
the three were jailed without bail as juveniles they faced a 
maximum of 10 years in prison at sentencing sept 11 
the 30yearold jogger was found lying senseless in a pool of 
blood after the april 19 1989 attack in a coma for two weeks 
she recovered enough to return to her investment banking job and 
give dramatic testimony at the trial 
the jury spent 10 days in deliberations the last three 
convincing one holdout who believed mccray was innocent it also 
took three days to consider the attempted murder charges said 
juror charles nestorick the jury finally decided to acquit because 
they believed the teenagers didnt intend to kill 
youths that age are not well versed in how many blows it takes 
to kill someone nestorick said 
the case created enormous sympathy for the victim whose name 
was not printed by most newspapers the defendants also had 
supporters who demonstrated outside the courthouse regularly 
charging racism because the victim was white and wealthy the 
youths black or hispanic 
defense attorneys claimed police lied and threatened santana and 
mccray into making videotaped confessions salaam did not sign a 
written statement or make a videotaped statement 
prosecutors said the three defendants were part of a gang of as 
many as 30 youths who rampaged through the park harassing at least 
nine people three other teenagers charged in the assault on the 
woman await trial two are free on bond 
salaam mccray and santana also were convicted of assault and 
robbery for attacks on two male joggers john loughlin and david 
lewis 
the woman was jogging through the northern end of the park when 
she was attacked she was dragged about 70 feet into the woods 
gangraped and bashed repeatedly with a brick and pipe 
she recovered enough to resume work and jogging within eight 
months of the attack she is a vice president for salomon brothers 
a wall street firm 
in a statement after the verdict mayor david dinkins said the 
attack seared the soul of every decent new yorker 
we should recommit ourselves to building a city and forging a 
society in which such heinous crimes do not occur he said 
while the womans recovery was inspirational to many new 
yorkers a few activists including the rev al sharpton claimed 
police arrested the youths because most were black 
earlier saturday the jurors had asked for the fourth time to 
see mccrays videotaped statement in which he told police he 
kicked the jogger and feigned sex with her to impress his friends 
mccrays father bobby mccray testified he encouraged his son 
to lie to police because he was led to believe there was an 
agreement that would allow his son to go free the detective who 
took the statement said no deal was offered 
another detective testified that santana told him he counted 33 
youths who entered the park shortly after 9 pm on the night of 
the attack to beat up and rip off joggers and cyclists 
when the group saw the female jogger on her nightly sixmile 
run we all charged her mccray said on the videotape she 
struggled and screamed as several teenagers dragged her from the 
paved drive down a wooded slope into the darkness he said 
the defendants told detectives the naked woman was struck with a 
metal pipe bashed in the head and face with a brick cut on the 
legs with a knife and sexually attacked in a frenzy of violence 
assistant district attorney elizabeth lederer said 
the trials most riveting moment came when the jogger took the 
witness stand she walked unsteadily before describing the lasting 
effects of the attack trouble with balance and sight no sense of 
smell a sixweek stretch of amnesia 
the rampaging youths went on to attack several other people 
loughlin a teacher hospitalized for two days with his injuries 
lewis a banker who escaped serious injury because of his speed 
and john goode a british airways employee who was punched 
medical workers testified the woman had lost about 
threequarters of her blood and was near death when she arrived at 
a hospital she later was transferred to a connecticut 
rehabilitation center 
the jurors criticized salaams attorney robert burns for 
putting his client on the stand 
it shot down everything he had going for him because his story 
was so farfetched nestorick said 
