<DOCNO> AP900819-0022 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
many people wept when fire razed 
historic chiado where the shop windows were full of dreams and 
cafes echoed with endless debate of art and politics two years 
later rebuilding is about to begin 
lisbon received messages of sympathy from cities and national 
governments after the fire it was showered with offers of help in 
recovering from a cultural disaster 
gone were the cafe ferrari scene of much good conversation and 
passionate argument window shopping on the rua do carmo the smell 
of roasting chestnuts in the old streets 
now the man who will direct the reconstruction says it may have 
been a blessing in disguise 
when the chiado burned the first news that went around the 
world was disaster in fact it was bad but not that bad 
alvaro siza vieira portugals leading architect said in an 
interview 
siza is ready to begin a 74 million rebuilding project in the 
10block downtown area that is expected to take three years 
the goal is regeneration of an area that before the fire was a 
bit ill and dilapidated he said strolling through the ruins of 
the grandela department store where the fire started aug 25 1988 
it raged for more than a day killing two people injuring 40 
leaving 300 homeless and 6000 temporarily out of work 
only charred ruins remained of such landmarks as the ferrari 
cafe specialty grocers costa e martins and the 350yearold casa 
batalha button shop on rua garrett 
the disaster inspired a debate worthy of the ferrari on topics 
ranging from city planning to safety standards 
most of the woodframe buildings had no fire sprinklers stone 
terraces in a new pedestrian mall kept fire trucks away from the 
heart of the blaze 
many lisbon residents proud of the beauty of a city stretching 
over seven hills along the shimmering tagus estuary worried that 
modern office blocks might be built in the old baixa or lower town 
in 1985 controversial architect tomas taveira shocked the city 
by building the amoreiras a massive pastelcolored shopping 
apartment and office complex atop one of the citys hills the 
amoreiras is a commercial success but few lisbon inhabitants say 
they like its style 
faced with this traditionalmodern rivalry siza departed from 
the contemporary ascetic style that won him the alvar aalto 
international architecture award in 1988 
it would have been wrong to use an accident to make an island 
of modern architecture in the historic center of lisbon he said 
chiado will look much the same as before he said because 18 of 
the 20 charred facades now propped by scaffolding can be saved but 
there will be new hidden improvements and the district wont 
be a museum 
the project approved by mayor jorge sampaio last month 
includes a luxury hotel and smallscale shopping malls behind the 
facades 
up to 40 percent of space on upper floors of reconstructed 
buildings will be devoted to apartments to keep people in the 
chiado not offices the architect said 
a new subway station will link the district with the baixa 
which was rebuilt on a grid system by the marquis of pombal after 
an earthquake destroyed most of lisbon in 1755 
one victim of the quake was the carmo convent siza plans a 
pedestrian ramp leading up to the convent ruins which have become 
part of lisbons skyline and to the labyrinth of trendy bars and 
restaurants in the narrow cobbled streets of the bairro alto or 
upper town 
the stone terraces on the rua do carmo that stopped the fire 
trucks will be ripped up and the street reopened to limited traffic 
mayor sampaio said the chiado project would set a precedent for 
restoring other parts of the city some of which date to the 11th 
century 
two areas that need renovation are alfama and mouraria where 
the rosepink and ocher houses usually are in bad repair because 
regulated low rents do not leave the owners enough money to fix 
them 
city housing expert vasco franco said 15 neglected houses 
collapsed in last winters heavy rains and he hoped foreign 
financing could be obtained perhaps from the european community 
