<TEXT>
she arrived in central park just another 
anonymous new york runner she came out of a coma 15 days later as 
a tabloid headline a victim of unspeakable crime and a symbol of 
hope in a city choked by violence 
shes known to millions now but still maintains her anonymity 
to all but a handful she is as nameless and faceless as she was on 
april 19 1989 her remarkable recovery inspired the city just as 
the brutality of her assault had horrified it 
the central park jogger 
she was found lying in a puddle of mud and blood early on april 
20 unconscious she arrived at metropolitan hospital a short time 
later an unlikely candidate for survival much less recovery she 
seemed destined to become another fatality in a record year for 
homicides 
her skull had been fractured threequarters of her blood was 
gone splattered around the roadway crossing the park her body 
temperature had dipped into the 80s 
she needed a machine to breathe her body was bruised literally 
from head to toe with severe head lacerations brain contusions 
and fractured facial bones 
photos of her injuries produced looks of dismay and disbelief 
from a jury which sat pokerfaced through six weeks of graphic 
testimony about her injuries 
on a scale of 3 to 15 used by neurologists to measure brain 
function the woman was rated a 4 even as she began to emerge from 
the coma attending physician dr howard s kurtz put her chances 
for full recovery at slim 
slowly steadily she came back new yorkers were cheered by 
reports of her highfiving a nurse of a soft hello to her 
brother 
she had no recollection of the events that changed her life her 
last memory before the attack was canceling dinner with a friend 
her next was waking up in the hospital for the memorial day weekend 
her progress could be charted by the holidays rapid improvement 
in a connecticut rehabilitation center by labor day back home 
and out jogging again for thanksgiving back at work by 
christmas and ringing in the new year with a promotion to vice 
president at salomon brothers 
