<TEXT>
a plan to ration services provided by 
oregons medicaid program to ensure that basic health care is 
available to the largest number of people has fallen more than a 
year behind schedule 
approved by the legislature in 1989 the program is the nations 
first to consider eliminating expensive or ineffective treatments 
for medicaid patients instead of providing total care as most 
states do 
a key to the program is an effort to establish a priority 
ranking of medical procedures that will be used to draw the line on 
medicaid spending 
but that effort encountered criticism when an initial ranking 
put crooked teeth near the top of its list and aids treatment near 
the bottom 
moreover critics say any reduction in medicaid coverage sets a 
dangerous precedent 
but state medicaid director jean thorne says health care costs 
are increasing at an alarming rate and she would far prefer to 
ration services than reduce the number of people who qualify for 
medicaid 
we constantly hear weve got to do something well 
theres no way we can attack this problem without being 
controversial she said if the critics dont have anything 
better to offer why not let us try this 
major health coverage celebrated its silver anniversary just 
last month on july 30 1965 president lyndon johnson signed into 
law medicare and medicaid its companion health plan for the poor 
medical spending increased from 38 billion in 1965 to 70 
billion in 1970 by 1980 health care costs had reached 236 
billion 
in 1983 the program was retooled payments to doctors and 
hospitals decreased and what constitutes the poor was redefined 
in oregon that meant a 6yearold whose parents earn 575 a 
month was entitled to a heart transplant but if the familys 
income totaled 576 a month that child could not get so much as a 
booster shot 
even so the states medicaid budget increased from 250 million 
during the 198587 biennium to 520 million during the current 
twoyear budget period according to thorne 
thats a 106 percent increase in funding but the number of 
people covered has increased by only 33 percent thorne said 
if were going to increase spending lets spread the money 
around more equitably 
the medicaid rationing program approved by the 1989 
legislature originally was to have begun on july 1 but state 
officials now concede there is little chance it will be ready by 
july 1 1991 
an 11member panel of doctors health care administrators and 
consumers has been poring over the priority list since september 
they spent months devising a mathematical formula that would weigh 
the cost of a medical procedure against the severity of an illness 
and the benefit of treatment 
detection and prevention of aids was high on the list but 
treatment for aids when a patient is close to death is near the 
bottom so are liver and bone marrow transplants which can run 
into the hundreds of thousands of dollars 
 
thumb sucking was 37th ahead of croup and congenital syphilis 
thats because common ailments like thumb sucking are easily 
treated at a relatively low cost 
the first draft was a data dump said paige sipesmetzler 
executive director of the oregon health services commission 
there will be another draft possibly more than one but for the 
time being we have something to work with 
in june the panel split into two subcommittees each taking a 
different approach to the priority list 
the panel has postponed until september any further decision on 
a ranking method meanwhile no deadline has been set for the next 
draft of the priority list 
we felt it was more important to get an extension of the 
deadline than to produce a list that doesnt work said 
sipesmetzler adding its never going to be a perfect list or 
satisfy everybody but at least people will understand it 
